<s> a spokesman for the customs and excise department said today ( friday ) that it is a serious offence to furnish false information for export licence application . </s>
<s> the warning was given after a garment manufacturer was fined $ 650,000 at north kowloon magistracy today after pleading guilty of making false statements regarding the origin of goods in export licence application . </s>
<s> the goods involved were 30,607 pieces of cotton knitted shirts and t @-@ shirts valued at about $ 2.64 million , for export to the european_union . </s>
<s> the court heard that between november 1995 and january 1996 , winzen knitwear limited submitted nine applications for export licences to the trade department covering the goods in question for export to eu . in the support of each application , </s>
<s> however , investigations by officers of the customs and excise department revealed that the statements made by winzen were false . </s>
<s> all the said goods were in fact manufactured by a factory in china as arranged by winzen due to a tight shipment schedule . </s>
<s> the spokesman stressed that the department would step up their enforcement actions to track down such malpractices to protect the commercial reputation of hong_kong and to ensure that the confidence of its trading partners in hong_kong 's textiles controls system would not be undermined by some dishonest businessmen . </s>
<s> the maximum penalty for making a false statement in export licence application is a fine of $ 500,000 plus two years ' imprisonment . </s>
<s> " members of the public having information on any suspected illegal textile transhipment activities could call the hotline 2804 2388. " he added . </s>
